UAS INCIDENT: 2212 The Pilot ofAAL1678departing RWY27R reported a white UAS over RWY27R moving S bound across the airport. ATL ATCT also observed the UAS flying across the Airport South bound towards the approach area for RWY27L just as DAL2046 was on short-final to this Runway. ATL ATCT instructed DAL2046 tocancel itsapproach and go-around due to the close proximity of the UAS. ATL ATCT also observed a grey and black SUV parked on the access road on the South side of the Airport and an individual standing outside the vehicle who appeared to be controlling the UAS. The Individual quicklygot in his vehicle and left the areaafter the DAL2046 approach was disrupted. ATL Airport Operations was notified and they dispatched a vehicle to patrol the area with negative results. TSOC notified. MR notified.

DCA-1: Incident occurred at 1835 (1335L), first notification was made by Pentagon Police (Thomas Shannon) at 1925 (1425L). The Pentagon Police and Arlington PD received a report of a UAS being operated at 675 North Randolph Street, Arlington, VA. (approximately DCA300003.5). According to reports, the UAS was not being operated above the height of the building (unknown height / floors). It was also initially reported that they had received approval for the operation from the FAA. TSA NCRCC, FAA NCRCC and DCA ATCT were unable to locate any information on the operation. When Arlington PD arrived at the scene (1835Z /1335L),the UAS was flying and they ordered it down and the pilot complied immediately. They estimate that it had been flying for approximately 5 minutes. When FAANCRCC queried them reference having FAA approval, they replied that was not the case as the operator landed the aircraft immediately. POC for the Arlington PD: Lt Dan Murphy, 571-388-7853. UAS Operator: Edgar Romero, Washington Digital Media, 240-701-0797 who stated that he was working for the construction company who was erecting a pedestrian walkway for the owners of the building. MOR completed by DCA. MX notified.

The pilot of ASH6022 originally reported a bird strike at approximately the DCA315020, which is north of Sterling, VA just west of the Trump National Golf course.   The aircraft was heading south at altitude 2,700 feet setting up for a landing on runway 19L.  No injuries or damage to aircraft were reported.  The strike occurred about 0025 Zulu and aircraft landed 0029 Zulu without incident.  The pilot reported a bird strike, but upon inspection of the aircraft on the ground, the crew could not locate any normal signs of a bird strike, such as blood, feathers or anything biological.  The crew upon reflection said the strike did not sound like a bird which is usually a soft thud, but it sounded more like a sharp crack like a baseball bat.   Because of the lack of biological evidence and the sharp sound of impact, the crew believes they hit a UAS.  Fairfax County PD is being notified of this incident.  0154:  The Washington Operations Center (WOC) called the FAA DEN position and told them Mesa Airlines (ASH) had a maintenance crew re examine the aircraft and the airline is now changing this incident to Bird Strike.  The airline did not pass to the FAA why they changed this report.  NFA.

DCA-1: At 1407 Navy Security at the NOB reported 9 drones overflew the NOB heading northwest to southeast at 3,000 feet, no other information provided. The report was received from HQ DEN who received the report from the Regional Operations Center (ROC) at the Eastern Service Center (ESC) who received the report from the Chief of Police of the Naval Support Activity, Washington (NSAW). MX notified. 1620 Naval Support Activity Washington, Chief of Police Irizari, stated Petty Officer Munjoy and 3 Naval Watch Security Force officers at the NOB South Gate observed what appeared to be 9 fixed wing type drones SE bound at approximately 3,000 feet. No other reported sightings or detections in the area. PCT will file MOR. NFA.

1750 UPDATE: Petty Officer Munjoy has made a change to the direction of the possible drones sighted. After further thought he believes the possible drones were heading southwest toward Arlington Cemetery.

MIA TRACON called to report that security for Turkey Point Nuclear Power Plant had called them to report UAS activity over the facility. Turkey Point Power Plant is located 4NM SE of HST. HQ DEN took the name and number of the Security Company that works security for the plant. 0058 HQ DEN contacted Turkey Point Security. The Security Officer reported that they had 3 drones operating over the facility for roughly 50 minutes (1905-1950). The drones have since moved on, 2 went east over the water and one went west. Turkey Point Security disclosed they contacted HST and MIA to try to verify if the Facilities were aware of any approved drone operations with negative results. They also called the USCG to see if they could assist with the drones over the water. The drones were 3x3 ft with flashing red and white lights. HQ DEN checked with SOSC and confirmed there were no approved UAS operations in that area. HQ DEN then recommended Turkey Point Security contact Miami Dade 305-5985-6263 and report the drones and request their assistance in locating the operators of the UAS. Turkey Point Security also said they had a FBI number 305-944-9101 and HQ DEN recommended they make that report to them as well. 0120 Turkey Point Security made contact with Miami-Dade PD and they were going to send an officer out to take a report. HQ DEN left our direct number and requested Turkey Point Security contact us directly with any further updates.

Aircraft observed a UAS while orbiting at 3,800 feet, 3.5NM N of TUS. Evasive action was taken, PIC reported NMAC. AWO advised. 0640 TUS ATCT reports that AIR2 lost contact with the UAS in the vicinity of AVQ (Marana Regional Airport) after following it for over 60 minutes. UAS was observed climbing to an estimated 12,000 feet. AIR2 attempted to capture camera footage but was unable. UAS had been reported as a quad-copter but no further description due to nighttime conditions. AWO advised.

At 0155 ATCT observed a UAS fly over the field, W bound at 400-500 feet, 1 NM W of GSO Airport. Airport Operations notified at 336-665-5642. 0155 GSO ATCT reports to HQ DEN Airport Police are sweeping perimeter, UAS is still visible over departure corridor. ATCT is holding 2 IFR departures on RWY 23L due to proximity of UAS. 0210 UPDATE: GSO ATCT advised they utilized Opposite Direction Operations to depart RWY 5R with LBQ782 and VTM061. Arrivals will be utilizing RWY 23L. Local Police and Fire Department are continuing to sweep airport and perimeter for operator. 0238 UPDATE: GSO ATCT reports last sighting approximately 0230, UAS was north of the airport flying east/west lines. Operations returning to normal configuration, arriving and departing RWY 23L. GSO ATCT will file MOR. 0250 UPDATE: GSO ATCT observed the large UAS transition over the airport west to east, turning south at approximately 600 feet. UAS impacting airfield operations. Air Traffic Manager has directed ATCT to suspend operations UFN. Airfield Operations, Local Police and Fire Department continue to sweep airfield and perimeter for operator. 4 IFR arrivals potentially impacted for the 0400 hour, ZTL will track and report diversions and/or delays. 0335 UPDATE: NOTAM GSO 02/174 issued for UAS activity. AWO reports COVID-19 Vaccine Flight, FDX1041, is delaying departure at ORD due to UAS ongoing event. 0430 UPDATE: 0406 GSO ATCT reports UAS sighting by Airport Operations 1/2 NM N of Airport, N bound heading towards HWY 73. 0415 GSO ATCT reports UAS sighting by Airport Operations NE of the Airport on the extended centerline RWY 23L. Approximately 0400 ATCSCC has issued a Ground Stop for Air Traffic into GSO. ATCSCC reports 1 aircraft diversion, 7 aircraft in airborne holding, 7 aircraft captured in the Ground Stop as of 0430. FDX Operations still holding COVID-19 Vaccine flight on the ground in ORD to minimize risk of airborne holding or diversion. 0435 UPDATE: AMOC has been monitoring GSO UAS event and has observed no radar returns. GSO ATCT reports they have had no radar returns from UAS activity, however visual sightings reported by the ATCT, LEO and Airfield Operations. 0435 UPDATE: GSO Airfield Operations reports last verified/confirmed sighting was approximately 0300, UAS had steady green, flashing red lights and made no noise. Subsequent reports of UAS are unconfirmed by Airport Operations. 3 LEO Agencies are now involved in securing the airport perimeter and monitoring operations. 0440 CLOSEOUT: GSO ATCT reports to the ATCSCC they are now going to start accepting arrivals and departures, last sighting north of the airport. ATCSCC has notified FDX and stakeholders. AWO, JH, CT notified.

INITIAL/CLKOSEOUT: 1430 Kings Bay Naval Base reported UAS operating inside P-50 and possibly taking video of the sub base. The operator of he UAS was on a boat off the coast. Camden County SO was notified. Camden County SO located the boat and detained the operator. HQ DEN advised JAX to have Camden County SO collect as much info on the operator to be included in the MOR for the FSDO. JAX questioned if the suspect should be detained further, arrested, or released, and HQ DEN advised that was not a decision made at this office. 1717 HQ DEN contacted Special Agent Whigham with NCIS. NCIS confirmed that the UAS did penetrate the confines of P-50 but did not over fly the base and WASP was not activated. NCIS notified that it was fisherman trying to locate fish. Special Agent Whigham 912-230-1735. Camden County SO 912-+510-5100. AWO notified.

The pilot did sound concerned so the controller temporarily suspended the tower pattern and vectored N55296 to the northwest. The aircraft landed safely moments later.  Another aircraft inbound from the southeast was issued a right downwind entry to avoid the reported position of the drone.  Another aircraft had reported drones to the west of the airport moments earlier but this was a different UAS due to location and timing. No further sightings are indicated. Local law enforcement was notified. MOR closed.

METAR.CEDAR: KDCA 211735Z 10007KT 10SM FEW015 SCT050CB SCT080 BKN250 25/18 A2990 RMK AO2 PK WND 28044/1714 RAB09E34 TSB03E35 PRESFR OCNL LTGICCG VC E-SE CB VC E-SE MOV SE P0045 T02500178
SUMMARY.CEDAR: On Wednesday, July 21, 2021 US Supreme Court reported to US Capitol Police (USCP) Headquarters that a UAS Drone was reported flying in the area of First and Maryland Avenue, NE, Washington, DC and crashed into the northside of the Supreme Court Building.  Officers from US Supreme Court, US Capitol Police, USCP Crime Scene, and USCP JTTF arrived on scene to investigate.  A red drone was found in the bushes and an investigation to locate the operator of the drone was met with negative results.   US Capitol Police did not have any camera footage of the drone.  The investigation was completed and the US Supreme court returned to normal operations at 1430.  The reported UAS's closest range to DCA was 2 nautical miles.  No further action was taken.

REMARKS: DCA-1: ADW Base Police observed a UAS with red and green lights, off the east side of ADW base, DCA121009, while hovering and eventually southbound. Altitude and type unknown. ADW LEO notified at 301-981-2002. 0735Z  ADW Tower reports a UAS with white, red, and green lights, 35-50 feet above AF1 hanger. Base PD investigating. 0803 NCRCC called ADW PD and they confirmed that original sighting over east gate went dark, and reappeared over AF1 hanger about 15-20 minutes later. UAS was detected by electronic means and verified by sightings from two different PD teams. No counter measures used at this time. 0926 Closeout: No more sightings reported. ADW will do MOR. 0929 ADW Tower talked to PAG security and they said that they never saw the UAS that the base security was seeing. PAG security said all they saw were lights from overflight aircraft.
SUMMARY.CEDAR: AT APPROXIMATELY 0637Z ADW'S UAS COUNTERMEASURE SENSORS WERE ALERETED TO AN UNAUTHORIZED UAS OPERATING WITHIN THE BASE PERIMETER. THE ON-SCENE OFFICER INFORMED TOWER, VIA TELEPHONE, OF THE ACTIVITY, BUT WAS UNABLE TO PROVIDE ANY INFORMATION AS TO SIZE, TYPE, OR ALTITUDE, EXCEPT THAT THE INTRUDER HAD RED, GREEN, AND WHITE LIGHTS AND WAS TRAVELING SOUTHBOUND. THE UAS WAS ORIGINALLY SPOTED NEAR THE PEARL HARBOR GATE WHICH IS LOCATED NEAR THE SOUTHEAST CORNER OF THE AIRFIELD. VISUAL CONFIRMATION WITH THE UAS LIGHTS WAS REPORTED LOST AT APPROX 0715Z. AN ADDITIONAL SIGHTING WAS MADE AT APPROXIMATLY 0737Z OVER THE AIR FORCE ONE HANGER 19.  THIS SIGHTING WAS CONFRIMED BY ADW SECURITY FORCES. THE VERBAL REPORTS RELAYED TO TOWER MENTIONED RED, GREEN, AND WHITE LIGHT. NO PERCISE DISCRIPTION WAS EVER OBSERVED, EXCEPT THE COLOR OF ITS LIGHTS. THE UAS DISSAPPEARED FROM LAW ENFORCEMENTS VIEW AND NO DIRECT ACTION WAS TAKEN AGAINST THE INTRUDER. ADW ATC CONTROLLERS WERE NEVER ABLE TO VIUSALLY CONFIRM WITH LEO'S REPORTS OF UAS/UAP SIGHTINGS.
QAFINDINGS.CEDAR: Facility summary reviewed. At approximately 0637Z ADW UAS countermeasure sensors were alerted to an unauthorized UAS operating within the base perimeter. The on-scene officer informed ATCT, via telephone, of the activity, but was unable to provide any information as to size, type, or altitude, except that the intruder had red, green, and white lights and was traveling southbound. The UAS was originally spotted near the Pearl Harbor gate which is located near the southeast corner of the airfield. Visual confirmation with the UAS lights was reported lost at approximately 0715z. An additional sighting was made at approximately 0737z over the Air Force one hanger 19.  This sighting was confirmed by ADW security forces. The verbal reports relayed to tower mentioned red, green, and white lights. No precise description was ever observed, except the color of its lights. The UAS disappeared from law enforcements view and no direct action was taken against the intruder. ADW ATCT controllers were never able to visually confirm the UAS/UAP sightings. MOR closed.

SUMMARY.CEDAR: During periodic inspection of the RNAV-A at W31 we had to maneuver to avoid a small remote controlled aircraft. The aircraft was less than 3 feet in wingspan and appeared to be something that could be bought at a hobby shop. There is a house immediately off the departure end of RWY 02 and the aircraft was operating over the house. We were able to avoid the remote aircraft and continued the mission with no further incident. ZDC QC comments, this report was submitted to the Flight Safety Program from a deidentified safety submission 5 days after the event.
QAFINDINGS.CEDAR: Facility summary reviewed. N84 was conducting an evaluation of an RNAV-A approach for RWY 2 at W31 airport in ZDC airspace. The RNAV approach for RWY 2 has a Go-around procedure with an initial heading of 360 degrees after initial climb is established. There is a house off the departure end of the runway and N84 encountered a remote control airplane over that house. Evasive maneuvers were taken to avoid the R/C airplane but the flight proceeded normally afterwards. The pilot did not declare a NMAC. The aircraft wasn't receiving ATC services at the time. The report was summitted 5 days after the event. No authorities were notified. MOR closed.

SUMMARY.CEDAR:
On the evening of August 21st, 2021 - RPA3656, an E170, departed ORF and was turned towards HPW VOR (approximately a heading of 320 degrees - northwest-bound). RPA 3656 was climbed to an altitude of 160 by the departure controller. At approximately 2155Z, the pilot of RPA3656 reported seeing a black object straight ahead between 7000 and 8000 feet. When pressed for more information, the pilot was unable to confirm what kind of object was seen. He mentioned that it could have been a weather balloon, but in his own opinion, he did not believe it be so. He described the object as "black" and "stationary." The pilot did not get a TCAS alert, nor did he have to take any evasive actions - he merely continued on his flight plan with no other issues.

The DEN was notified at 2206Z at 844-432-2962.
The Norfolk Police Department was notified at 2210Z at 757-664-3277.
QAFINDINGS.CEDAR: Facility summary, weather and falcon bookmark reviewed. RPA3656 departed ORF and climbing westbound wen the pilot reported that they had passed an object somewhere between 7-8,000ft during the climb. Vertical and lateral proximity were neither requested nor given. The object was reported as black and stationary. No evasive maneuvers were reported and the flight proceeded normally. ATC services at ORF were not impacted. No further sightings were indicated. DEN and law enforcement were notified. MOR closed.

SUMMARY.CEDAR: ENY3961 DEPARTED RWY09C FOR DTW. ONE MILE OFF THE DEPARTURE END CLIMBING OUT OF 2500 FEET, HEADING 090 TURNING TO A 360 HEADING, ENY3961 STRUCK A DRONE BELOW THE RIGHT FRONT WINDSHIELD IN THE FORWARD FUSELAGE. ENY3961 DECLARED AN EMERGENCY. COORDINATED WITH THE DEN AND ORD ATCT. CONTACTED FBI AT 312-421-6700. 3700 POUNDS OF FUEL WITH 76 PEOPLE ON BOARD.
